  footnotes: []
english:
  title: A Modest Drink on a Snowy Night
  author: Lee Gok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    As the twelfth month draws near, snow barely shows its blessing,
    Winter stays warm yet loses not heaven's grace.
    Whose footsteps wake the earth at dawn upon the snow?
    Antlike tracks—the birds have left their marks in plenty.

    Old pursuits remain only by the books on the shelf,
    My promised homecoming forsaken for the fisherman's cloak.
    We gather round the glowing brazier, all of us strangers,
    Yet lacking coin for wine—what remedy remains?
  footnotes:
    - The reference to 'the fisherman's cloak' invokes the classical image of the recluse who abandons worldly affairs, suggesting the speaker has retreated from active life.
    - The gathering around the brazier evokes a sense of temporary refuge and fellowship among transient souls, emphasizing the speaker's displacement and melancholy.
